      <h1 class="blog-title">Circles: Sharing Your Book with Family, the Easy Way</h1>

      <p class="blog-meta">Feature &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 5 min read</p>

      <div class="blog-body">

        <p>Legacy Odyssey is a digital baby book — built as a real website at your child's own .com domain. Your baby gets their name as a website. Parents fill in milestones, photos, and letters through the iOS &amp; Android app. Family visits the book at your-childs-name.com, straight from any browser. Password-protected. $29 for the first year.</p>

        <p>Circles is the part that makes sharing simple: a private list of the people who can see the book, and a one-tap way to let them know when there's something new.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>What it is</h2>

        <p>Circles does two things.</p>

        <p><strong>It keeps your people organized.</strong> You add the family and friends who should see the book, and you can sort them into named groups — like "Grandparents" or "Close Family." That's a Circle.</p>

        <p><strong>It sends private links.</strong> When you add a new month or a fresh set of photos, you can send an update. Each person gets their own email with their own private link straight to the book — no password to type on their end.</p>

        <p>It's all in My Account, on the web at legacyodyssey.com/account/book/circles, and in the iOS and Android app. Same feature, same place, whichever you prefer.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Why it matters</h2>

        <p>The book already lives at your child's .com address, and it's password-protected. That works beautifully when you hand out the address and the password yourself.</p>

        <p>Circles is for everything after that. You don't have to keep re-texting the link and the password to one relative at a time, or worry about who you told and who you forgot. You build the list once. When there's news, you pick who to tell and Legacy Odyssey emails each of them a private link — they tap it and they're in. Grandma never has to remember a password, and you never have to chase anyone down.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>How to use it, step by step</h2>

        <h3>1. Open Your Circles</h3>

        <p>Sign in at legacyodyssey.com/account (or open the app) and go to <strong>My Account → Your Circles</strong>.</p>

        <h3>2. Add the people</h3>

        <p>Under <strong>People</strong>, fill in a name, and an email if you have one (a phone number is optional). Tap <strong>+ Add Person</strong>. Repeat for everyone you'd like to keep in the loop. Email is what lets you send someone an update later, so add it where you can.</p>

        <h3>3. Make a Circle or two (optional)</h3>

        <p>Under <strong>Circles</strong>, type a name like "Grandparents" and tap <strong>+ Add Circle</strong>. Then, on any person, open <strong>Edit</strong> and check the Circles they belong to. Someone can be in more than one. Circles are just groups — handy when you want to tell one part of the family something without emailing everybody.</p>

        <h3>4. Send an update</h3>

        <p>When there's something new in the book, the <strong>Send an Update</strong> panel appears at the top of the page. Choose <strong>Who</strong> — Everyone, or one specific Circle — add an optional short note like "New photos from the first birthday are up!", and tap <strong>Send Update</strong>.</p>

        <p>Each person on that list gets their own email with their own private link. They open the book in any browser, no password needed. To keep inboxes friendly, you can send one update every ten minutes.</p>

        <h3>5. Managing access over time</h3>

        <p>People stay on your list until you change it. Removing someone stops their private link from working. Deleting a Circle just ungroups those people — their contact details stay. And every update email includes a one-tap way for the recipient to unsubscribe themselves, so you're never the one managing that.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>An example</h2>

        <p>Say the book is for Sophia Smith, live at sophiasmith.com.</p>

        <p>Mom and Dad open Your Circles and add the people who should see it: both sets of grandparents, two aunts, and a couple of close friends. They make one Circle called <strong>Grandparents</strong> and add the four grandparents to it.</p>

        <p>A few weeks later, Sophia takes her first steps and Dad adds a new Month by Month entry with a short video still and a note. He opens Your Circles, picks <strong>Everyone</strong>, types "She's walking!! New photos in the book 🎉," and taps Send Update.</p>

        <p>Eight private links go out. Grandpa opens his on his phone over breakfast — one tap, straight to Sophia's book, no password, no app to install. The next month, when it's just a quiet set of new photos, Mom sends that one to the <strong>Grandparents</strong> Circle only.</p>

        <p>That's Circles: build the list once, then sharing the latest is a single tap.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>A note on the password</h2>

        <p>Circles doesn't replace your site password — it sits alongside it. The password is still there for anyone you hand the address to directly. Circles simply gives the people closest to you their own private way in, and gives you an easy way to say "there's something new."</p>

